Numerical definition

Fresh water can be defined as water with less than 500 [parts per million](/Parts_per_million) (ppm) of dissolved [salts](/Salt_(chemistry)). [6]

Other sources give higher upper salinity limits for fresh water, e.g. 1,000 ppm [7] or 3,000 ppm. [8]

## Systems

Fresh water habitats are classified as either [lentic systems](/Lake_ecosystem), which are the stillwaters including [ponds](/Pond), lakes, [swamps](/Swamp) and [mires](/Bog); [lotic](/Lotic) which are running-water systems; or [groundwaters](/Groundwater) which flow in rocks and [aquifers](/Aquifer). There is, in addition, a zone which bridges between groundwater and lotic systems, which is the [hyporheic zone](/Hyporheic_zone), which underlies many larger rivers and can contain substantially more water than is seen in the open channel. It may also be in direct contact with the underlying underground water.

## Sources

•
Main articles: [Water cycle](/Water_cycle) and [Water resources](/Water_resources)

The original source of almost all fresh water is [precipitation](/Precipitation_(meteorology)) from the [atmosphere](/Earth%27s_atmosphere), in the form of [mist](/Mist), [rain](/Rain) and [snow](/Snow). Fresh water falling as mist, rain or snow contains materials dissolved from the [atmosphere](/Atmosphere) and material from the sea and land over which the rain bearing clouds have traveled. The precipitation leads eventually to the formation of [water bodies](/Body_of_water) that humans can use as sources of freshwater: [ponds](/Pond), [lakes](/Lake), [rainfall](/Rain), [rivers](/River), [streams](/Stream), and [groundwater](/Groundwater) contained in underground [aquifers](/Aquifer).

In coastal areas fresh water may contain significant concentrations of salts derived from the sea if windy conditions have lifted drops of seawater into the rain-bearing clouds. This can give rise to elevated concentrations of [sodium](/Sodium), [chloride](/Chloride), [magnesium](/Magnesium) and [sulfate](/Sulfate) as well as many other compounds in smaller concentrations.

In [desert](/Desert) areas, or areas with impoverished or dusty soils, rain-bearing winds can pick up [sand](/Sand) and [dust](/Dust) and this can be deposited elsewhere in precipitation and causing the freshwater flow to be measurably contaminated both by insoluble solids but also by the soluble components of those soils. Significant quantities of [iron](/Iron) may be transported in this way including the well-documented transfer of iron-rich rainfall falling in Brazil derived from sand-storms in the [Sahara](/Sahara) in [north Africa](/North_Africa). [9]

In Africa, it was revealed that groundwater controls are complex and do not correspond directly to a single factor. Groundwater showed greater resilience to climate change than expected, and areas with an increasing threshold between 0.34 and 0.39 aridity index exhibited significant sensitivity to climate change. Land-use could affect infiltration and runoff processes. The years of most recharge coincided with the most precipitation anomalies, such as during [El Niño](/El_Ni%C3%B1o) and [La Niña](/La_Ni%C3%B1a) events. Three precipitation-recharge sensitivities were distinguished: in super arid areas with more than 0.67 aridity index, there was constant recharge with little variation with precipitation; in most sites (arid, semi-arid, humid), annual recharge increased as annual precipitation remained above a certain threshold; and in complex areas down to 0.1 aridity index (focused recharge), there was very inconsistent recharge (low precipitation but high recharge). Understanding these relationships can lead to the development of sustainable strategies for water collection. This understanding is particularly crucial in Africa, where water resources are often scarce and climate change poses significant challenges. [10]

## Water distribution

Visualisation of the distribution (by volume) of water on Earth [a]
A graphical distribution of the locations of water on Earth [b]

•
Main article: [Water distribution on Earth](/Water_distribution_on_Earth)

Saline water in [oceans](/Ocean), [seas](/Sea) and saline [groundwater](/Groundwater) make up about 97% of all the water on [Earth](/Earth). Only 2.5–2.75% is fresh water, including 1.75–2% frozen in [glaciers](/Glacier), [ice](/Ice) and snow, 0.5–0.75% as fresh groundwater. The water table is the level below which all spaces are filled with water, while the area above this level, where spaces in the rock and soil contain both air and water, is known as the unsaturated zone. The water in this unsaturated zone is referred to as soil moisture.

Below the water table, the entire region is known as the saturated zone, and the water in this zone is called groundwater. [12] Groundwater plays a crucial role as the primary source of water for various purposes including drinking, washing, farming, and manufacturing, and even when not directly used as a drinking water supply it remains vital to protect due to its ability to carry contaminants and pollutants from the land into lakes and rivers, which constitute a significant percentage of other people's freshwater supply. It is almost ubiquitous underground, residing in the spaces between particles of rock and soil or within crevices and cracks in rock, typically within 100 m (330 ft) of the surface, [12] and [soil](/Soil) moisture, and less than 0.01% of it as [surface water](/Surface_water) in [lakes](/Lake), [swamps](/Swamp) and [rivers](/River). [13][14]

Freshwater lakes contain about 87% of this fresh surface water, including 29% in the [African Great Lakes](/African_Great_Lakes), 22% in [Lake Baikal](/Lake_Baikal) in Russia, 21% in the [North American Great Lakes](/North_American_Great_Lakes), and 14% in other lakes. Swamps have most of the balance with only a small amount in rivers, most notably the [Amazon River](/Amazon_River). The atmosphere contains 0.04% water. [15] In areas with no fresh water on the ground surface, fresh water derived from [precipitation](/Precipitation_(meteorology)) may, because of its lower density, overlie saline ground water in lenses or layers. Most of the world's fresh water is frozen in [ice sheets](/Ice_sheet). Many areas have very little fresh water, such as [deserts](/Desert).

## Freshwater ecosystems

Water is a critical issue for the survival of all living organisms. Some can use salt water but many organisms including the great majority of higher plants and most [mammals](/Mammal) must have access to fresh water to live. Some terrestrial mammals, especially desert [rodents](/Rodent), appear to survive without drinking, but they do generate water through the [metabolism](/Metabolism) of [cereal](/Cereal) seeds, and they also have mechanisms to conserve water to the maximum degree.

•
This section is an excerpt from [Freshwater ecosystem](/Freshwater_ecosystem).[edit]

Freshwater ecosystem

[Freshwater ecosystems](/Freshwater_ecosystem) are a subset of Earth's [aquatic ecosystems](/Aquatic_ecosystem) that include the [biological communities](/Biological_communities) inhabiting [freshwater](/Freshwater) [waterbodies](/Waterbodies) such as [lakes](/Lake_ecosystem), [ponds](/Pond), [rivers](/River_ecosystem), [streams](/Stream), [springs](/Spring_(hydrosphere)), [bogs](/Bogs), and [wetlands](/Wetland). [16] They can be contrasted with [marine ecosystems](/Marine_ecosystem), which have a much higher [salinity](/Salinity). Freshwater habitats can be classified by different factors, including temperature, light penetration, nutrients, and vegetation.

There are three basic types of freshwater ecosystems: [lentic](/Lentic_system_ecology) (slow moving water, including [pools](/Stream_pool), [ponds](/Pond), and [lakes](/Lakes)), [lotic](/Lotic_System_Ecology) (faster moving [streams](/Stream), for example [creeks](/Stream) and [rivers](/River)) and [wetlands](/Wetland) ([semi-aquatic](/Semi-aquatic) areas where the soil is saturated or inundated for at least part of the time). [17][16] Freshwater ecosystems contain 41% of the world's known [fish](/Fish) species. [18]

## Challenges

•
Main article: [Water resources § Challenges and threats](/Water_resources)

•
Further information: [Human impacts on the environment](/Human_impacts_on_the_environment) and [Freshwater ecosystem § Threats](/Freshwater_ecosystem)

The increase in the world population and the increase in per capita water use puts increasing strains on the finite resources availability of clean fresh water. The response by [freshwater ecosystems](/Freshwater_ecosystem) to a [changing climate](/Climate_change) can be described in terms of three interrelated components: water quality, water quantity or volume, and water timing. A change in one often leads to shifts in the others as well. [19]

### Limited resource

•
•
This section is an excerpt from [Water scarcity](/Water_scarcity).[edit]

[Water scarcity](/Water_scarcity) (closely related to water stress or [water crisis](/Water_crisis_(disambiguation))) is the lack of fresh water [resources](/Water_resources) to meet the standard water demand. There are two types of water scarcity. One is physical. The other is economic water scarcity . [20] : 560 Physical water scarcity is where there is not enough water to meet all demands. This includes water needed for [ecosystems](/Ecosystem) to function. Regions with a [desert climate](/Desert_climate) often face physical water scarcity. [21] [Central Asia](/Central_Asia), [West Asia](/West_Asia), and [North Africa](/North_Africa) are examples of arid areas. Economic water scarcity results from a lack of investment in infrastructure or technology to draw water from rivers, [aquifers](/Aquifer), or other water sources. It also results from weak human capacity to meet water demand. [20] : 560 Many people in [sub-Saharan Africa](/Sub-Saharan_Africa) are living with economic water scarcity. [22] : 11

There is enough freshwater available globally and averaged over the year to meet demand. As such, water scarcity is caused by a mismatch between when and where people need water, and when and where it is available. [23] This can happen due to an [increase in the number of people](/Population_growth) in a region, changing living conditions and diets, and expansion of [irrigated agriculture](/Irrigation). [24][25][26] [Climate change](/Climate_change) (including [droughts](/Droughts) or [floods](/Floods)), [deforestation](/Deforestation), [water pollution](/Water_pollution) and wasteful use of water can also mean there is not enough water. [27] These variations in scarcity may also be a function of prevailing [economic policy](/Economic_policy) and planning approaches.

### Minimum streamflow

•
Further information: [Water scarcity § Environment](/Water_scarcity)

An important concern for hydrological ecosystems is securing minimum [streamflow](/Streamflow), especially preserving and restoring [instream water allocations](/Instream_use). [28] Fresh water is an important natural resource necessary for the survival of all [ecosystems](/Ecosystem).

### Water pollution

•
•
This section is an excerpt from [Water pollution](/Water_pollution).[edit]

[Water pollution](/Water_pollution) (or aquatic pollution) is the contamination of [water bodies](/Body_of_water), with a negative impact on their uses. [29] : 6 It is usually a result of human activities. Water bodies include [lakes](/Lake), [rivers](/River), [oceans](/Ocean), [aquifers](/Aquifer), [reservoirs](/Reservoir) and [groundwater](/Groundwater). Water [pollution](/Pollution) results when [contaminants](/Contaminant) mix with these water bodies. Contaminants can come from one of four main sources. These are [sewage](/Sewage) discharges, industrial activities, agricultural activities, and urban runoff including [stormwater](/Stormwater). [30] Water pollution may affect either [surface water](/Surface_water) or [groundwater](/Groundwater_pollution). This form of pollution can lead to many problems. One is the [degradation](/Environmental_degradation) of [aquatic ecosystems](/Aquatic_ecosystems). Another is spreading [water-borne diseases](/Waterborne_diseases) when people use polluted water for drinking or [irrigation](/Irrigation). [31] Water pollution also reduces the [ecosystem services](/Ecosystem_service) such as [drinking water](/Drinking_water) provided by the [water resource](/Water_resources).

Sources of water pollution are either [point sources](/Point_source) or [non-point sources](/Non-point_source). [32] Point sources have one identifiable cause, such as a [storm drain](/Storm_drain), a [wastewater treatment plant](/Wastewater_treatment_plant), or an [oil spill](/Oil_spill). Non-point sources are more diffuse. An example is [agricultural runoff](/Surface_runoff). [33] Pollution is the result of the cumulative effect over time. Pollution may take many forms. One would is toxic substances such as oil, metals, plastics, [pesticides](/Pesticide), [persistent organic pollutants](/Persistent_organic_pollutant), and industrial waste products. Another is stressful conditions such as changes of [pH](/PH), [hypoxia](/Hypoxia_(environmental)) or anoxia, increased temperatures, excessive [turbidity](/Turbidity), or changes of [salinity](/Salinity)). The introduction of [pathogenic organisms](/Pathogen) is another. Contaminants may include [organic](/Organic_compound) and [inorganic](/Inorganic) substances. A common cause of [thermal pollution](/Thermal_pollution) is the use of water as a [coolant](/Coolant) by [power plants](/Power_plants) and industrial manufacturers.

## Society and culture

### Human uses

•
Main article: [Water resources § Water uses](/Water_resources)

Uses of water include [agricultural](/Agricultural), [industrial](/Industrial_sector), [household](/Household), [recreational](/Recreational) and [environmental](/Natural_environment) activities.

### Global goals for conservation

The [Sustainable Development Goals](/Sustainable_Development_Goals) are a collection of 17 interlinked global goals designed to be a "blueprint to achieve a better and more [sustainable](/Sustainability) future for all". [34] Targets on fresh [water conservation](/Water_conservation) are included in [SDG 6](/Sustainable_Development_Goal_6) (Clean water and sanitation) and [SDG 15](/Sustainable_Development_Goal_15) (Life on land). For example, Target 6.4 is formulated as "By 2030, substantially increase [water-use efficiency](/Water-use_efficiency) across all sectors and ensure sustainable withdrawals and [supply of freshwater](/Water_supply) to address water scarcity and substantially reduce the number of people suffering from [water scarcity](/Water_scarcity)." [34] Another target, Target 15.1, is: "By 2020, ensure the conservation, restoration and sustainable use of terrestrial and inland [freshwater ecosystems](/Freshwater_ecosystem) and their services, in particular forests, [wetlands](/Wetland), [mountains](/Mountain) and [drylands](/Drylands), in line with obligations under international agreements." [34]

